name: Luxury w/terrace near the beach Wif
description:
The apartment is located in the mezzanine of a building in the neighbourhood of Antiguo.

It has 2 bedrooms, 2 bathrooms, a kitchen and a spacious living-dining room. It also has a 30 m2 terrace.

Well mannered pets are welcomed.
neighborhood_overview:
In this neighborhood with a strong personality, which originally emerged as an industrial and working-class neighborhood, a great change has taken place in recent years.
The various common facilities - Sports Centers, the Market, the House of Culture - contribute to greater mobility in the neighborhood.

It is located to west of La Concha Bay, it is bordered to the north by Igeldo, to the southwest by Ibaeta and to the southeast by Aiete.

The houses of Ondarreta and BentaBerri, in addition to increasing their population, have had a qualitative influence on the life of the neighborhood.
host_about:
My name is Emy and I am the owner of these apartments. I was born and raised in San Sebastian and I love to help my guests enjoy this wonderful city and all it has to offer so that they leave happy and impressed by the beauty and the quality of life (not to mention the food, of course!) of San Sebastian.
I am very well travelled and still love to travel, so I know exactly what people need to know about a foreign city to fully enjoy their stay. 
I rented my first apartment in 2007 and since then I keep adding new apartments after fully refurbishing them to offer my guests nice environments.
I am a very active, friendly and happy person, and apart from traveling and meeting people from all over the world, there are a lot of things I love like good food, good wines, ecological gardening, cats, Mac and photography mainly.
If you decide to come to one of my apartments, be sure I will make sure you have the very best stay in San Sebastian.

name: Casa en Dima. Bilbao (Vizcaya)
description:
House in Dima, 30' from Bilbao, Vitoria and 1 h from San Sebastian and Pamplona. It is located next to the Gorbeia natural park and in less than 1 hour by car you can visit villages such as Gernika and Durango, natural parks (Urkiola or the Urdaibai biosphere), vineyards of La Rioja and the entire Basque coast (Bermeo, Elantxobe, Lekeitio, Getaria, Zarautz...).
Wide terrain and magnificent views of the valley of Arratia.
Newly built house. (Reg.: EBI-156)
neighborhood_overview: The house is located in a quiet but not solitary place, built on the edge of a natural balcony overlooking the valley and facing the Gorbeia massif. neighborhood_overview:
Gorliz belongs to the region of Uribe Kosta. The area
of the municipality is 10.29 km2 and is located 25 km from Bilbao. It borders Lemoiz to the east and Plentzia to the south. Its population is 5,708 inhabitants, in summer it quadruples.
The total coast of Gorliz has more than 4 km. Its beach or sand is adjacent to Plentzia. A golden, fine-grained shell-shaped beach near Greater Bilbao with calm, safe waters makes it one of the most visited beaches in the entire Historical Territory of Biscay and ideal for all types of water sports.
On the 1.33 km walk, 9 meters wide (of which 3 are intended for bike lanes) we find the Gorliz Hospital / Sanatorium.
Two kilometres from the Butron estuary pass through the municipality. There are three streams that flow into the beach: Kukuluerreka, Gazatza and Txatxarro.
Astondo dunes and dunes recovered in sand.
Picnic area "El Pinar” by the beach

About San Sebastian
From beautiful sandy beaches and rolling green hills, to designer shops and Michelin starred restaurants, San Sebastian - or as it is known by its Basque name, Donostia - has everything to offer. Whether you have come to surf the waves of Zurriola, eat pintxos and taste the local “sidra”, or to walk the Camino del Norte, it will surely be a trip you won’t forget!

neighborhood_overview:
Plentzia is a pleasant and cozy coastal town located about 25 kilometers from Bilbao, in a beautiful bay that overlooks the sea and that it shares with neighboring Gorliz.

Founded in 1299, this town still preserves part of its historical legacy. Its picturesque old town, of medieval origin, brilliantly combines popular seafaring architecture with more cultured and palatial buildings. It is worth getting lost in its narrow streets and contemplating authentic jewels such as the Church of Santa María Magdalena, which stands out for its beautiful 16th century tower, or the old town hall built in ashlar masonry and which houses the Plazentia Butrón Museum, where elements are displayed of the history of this coastal town.

name: La casa del patio
description: Small independent apartment in the Trápaga Valley, specifically in the Arboleda.
neighborhood_overview:
LA ARBOLEDA

The iron mountains that surround this urban core, the Triano Mountains, witness the change that this area has undergone throughout history. A transformation, which we can check in the first person by visiting the Peñas Negras Interpretation Center, where we found several photographs that show us the before and after the mining boom that La Arboleda suffered. Amazing. The mining has changed the landscape completely. The reddish color of the rocks rich in iron and the green of its mountains, are today 2 of the signs of identity of La Arboleda. A natural space full of history that we recommend visiting.

Although this is a very small urban core, La Arboleda has a lot of attractions to visit. In addition, its location, 30 minutes from the center of Bilbao, in the middle of the mining area, invites us to visit many other spaces of interest.

name: Coqueto apartamento cerca del  casco Viejo
description: Cozy two bedroom apartment very close to Casco Viejo.
neighborhood_overview: It is very close to the  Casco Viejo de Bilbao (very central) in a neighborhood called Bilbao La Vieja, popularly known as Bilbi or as small Botxo (it is a multicultural neighborhood). It has some restaurants and some special bars for drinks or beers. But if you want much more to choose from, you can get close to the old town that is a 3-minute walk away and there you have wonderful bars and restaurants to eat pintxos, menus of the day or the typical Bilbao cazuelitas. Also two minutes away is the famous Mercado de la Ribera (one of the largest closed markets in Europe. You have stalls to buy the best meat and fish or the best fruits and vegetables. But it also has  a wonderful "gastro-lunch" area overlooking the river. An unsafe one that you can't miss.
